    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-02-09T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-02-09T13:00:00-05:00" n="364"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d364">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A.R.–N.C./44: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hinkle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ciudad Trujillo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-02-09T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 9, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Department’s circular January 27, 3 p.m. Dominion [<hi rend="italic"
                        >Dominican</hi>] Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="43" xml:id="d364fn1"
                        >Arturo Despradel.</note> today said that he would issue instructions
                    shortly to his representative in Rio which will be in accordance with the
                    Department’s views on the Neutrality Committee. The serious illness of the
                    President during the past few weeks was, according to the Secretary, delaying
                    approval of such matters.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hinkle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
